<div class="revisioninfo">Page view:</div><h4>Write DES Data</h4>

<br />
Writing DES data is slightly different between 1.5 and 2.0.  There is an example in the repository (test_create_des.c) that is a good example for how to add TREs and it will be fairly different depending on which version of NITRO you are using.<br />
<br />
The DES is quite possibly the most confusing segment in the NITF file.  That is because it can have a number of different representations.  Internally, a DES has several optional user-defined headers.  These values correspond to DESSHL and DESSHF in the spec.  These user-defined fields kind of make a DES look like their own TRE.  In fact, NITRO 1.5 uses the same data structure to represent these fields (TRE) as it does for the TREs.  However, the DES content itself is defined as a 'user-defined TRE with no intervening octets' -- a potentially quite-large sub-section called DESDATA.  This data could actually be overflow from other TREs -- designated by the DES ID 'TRE_OVERFLOW.'  In this case NITRO treats the data as a sequence of TREs, and uses the available handlers to read it.  This data is stored in the subhdr-&gt;userDefinedSection.<br />
